column1: In the past two weeks, have you felt down, depressed, or unusually low during your shifts or at home?
column2: Have you had a persistent sense of sadness or low mood that lasts throughout workdays or days off?
column3: Have you found yourself losing interest in activities (on or off shift) that you normally enjoy or find meaningful?
column4: Have you been feeling unusually drained or exhausted, even when you’ve had adequate rest between shifts?
column5: Have you had trouble concentrating on tasks, reports, training, or making quick decisions that you normally handle easily?
column6: Have you been struggling with sleep, such as difficulty falling asleep, waking up frequently, or sleeping far more than usual, especially around your shift schedule?
column7: Have you noticed feeling unusually restless, “keyed-up,” or, on the other hand, moving or reacting more slowly than usual during your shifts?
column8: Have you had thoughts of not wanting to be here anymore, or thoughts about harming yourself, especially after stressful calls or shifts?
column9: Have you experienced changes in appetite or weight—such as eating much more or less—unrelated to fitness training or shift demands?
column10: Have you found yourself caring less about parts of the job or personal life that used to matter to you?
column11: Have you felt detached, numb, or disconnected from your crew, patients, family, or friends?
column12: Have you struggled to feel positive emotions—like pride in your work, enjoyment with your team, or joy in your personal life—even when things go well?
column13: Have you found it harder than usual to stay focused during calls, training, or day-to-day tasks?
